\begin{abstract}
We present a Hamiltonian Crystal framework that naturally generates the Koide relation for charged leptons and extends to neutrino masses. Using Fock-space lattice modes, discrete spectral gaps, and gauge-invariant portal couplings, the model predicts both absolute lepton masses and tiny time-crystal-induced oscillatory corrections. Testable predictions include deviations from the canonical Koide parameter $Q=2/3$, neutrino mass ordering, and ultra-low-frequency vacuum modulations. Illustrative diagrams depict the lattice, spectral gaps, and portal interactions, providing a geometric and experimentally actionable perspective.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
The Koide formula
\begin{equation}
Q = \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau})^2} \approx \frac{2}{3}
\end{equation}
remains an intriguing empirical relation. Here we show that embedding leptons and neutrinos in a Hamiltonian Crystal with discrete spectral gaps and integer Fock-space occupation naturally reproduces $Q\sim 2/3$, while providing predictions for neutrino masses and time-dependent mass modulations.

\section{Fock-Space Hamiltonian for Leptons}
Define a three-mode Hamiltonian with off-diagonal portal couplings:
\begin{equation}
H_{\rm leptons} =
\begin{pmatrix}
\Delta E_1 & g_{12} & g_{13} \\
g_{12} & \Delta E_2 & g_{23} \\
g_{13} & g_{23} & \Delta E_3
\end{pmatrix},
\end{equation}
where $\Delta E_i$ are spectral gaps and $g_{ij}$ are portal interactions. The eigenvalues correspond to physical lepton masses:
\begin{equation}
m_i = E_i / c_{\rm crystal}^2.
\end{equation}

\subsection{Koide Parameter from Fock-Space Eigenvalues}
The Koide parameter is
\begin{equation}
Q = \frac{m_1 + m_2 + m_3}{(\sqrt{m_1} + \sqrt{m_2} + \sqrt{m_3})^2}.
\end{equation}
Deviations $\delta Q$ arise from off-diagonal couplings and lattice perturbations $\epsilon_i$:
\begin{equation}
\delta Q \sim f(\epsilon_1, \epsilon_2, \epsilon_3, g_{ij}).
\end{equation}

\section{Neutrino Masses and Ordering}
Extending the Hamiltonian to neutrino Fock modes:
\begin{equation}
H_\nu =
\begin{pmatrix}
\Delta E_{\nu_1} & g_{\nu_{12}} & g_{\nu_{13}} \\
g_{\nu_{12}} & \Delta E_{\nu_2} & g_{\nu_{23}} \\
g_{\nu_{13}} & g_{\nu_{23}} & \Delta E_{\nu_3}
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{equation}
Eigenvalues predict absolute neutrino masses $m_{\nu_i}$.  
Depending on the lattice structure and portal couplings, neutrinos may be Dirac or Majorana; specific $g_{\nu_i f_j}$ values determine lepton-number conservation.

\section{Time-Crystal Corrections}
Periodic driving of vacuum modes leads to oscillatory corrections:
\begin{equation}
m_i(t) = m_i^{(0)} + \delta m_i \cos(\omega_i t),
\end{equation}
with $\omega_i \sim \Delta E_{\rm vac} / \hbar_{\rm crystal}$. These produce tiny but calculable deviations in $Q$ and potentially observable modulations in neutrino oscillation probabilities.

