\section{Experimental Predictions}

\begin{itemize}
\item Koide parameter $Q$ deviations: $\delta Q \sim 10^{-5}-10^{-3}$ depending on $g_{ij}$.
\item Neutrino masses (normal ordering): $m_{\nu_1}\sim 0.005$ eV, $m_{\nu_2}\sim0.01$ eV, $m_{\nu_3}\sim0.05$ eV (example values from lattice parameters).
\item Time-crystal oscillations: frequencies $\omega_i \sim 10^{25}$ Hz at lattice scale; effective cosmological averaging may produce observable ultra-low-frequency modulations.
\item Portal-mediated interactions could induce rare visible-dark sector transitions, testable in precision experiments.
\end{itemize}

\section{Conclusion}
The Hamiltonian Crystal provides a natural geometric and lattice-based explanation for the Koide relation, while extending to neutrino masses, oscillations, and time-crystal effects. The framework is falsifiable: precise measurements of $Q$, neutrino mass sums, and ultra-low-frequency modulations could confirm or refute the model.

